{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":275470,"duration_api_ms":407279,"num_turns":27,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"67d19fcd-0054-4f4a-9f86-f66cb21a4d17","total_cost_usd":1.4334898,"usage":{"input_tokens":18,"cache_creation_input_tokens":54314,"cache_read_input_tokens":861833,"output_tokens":6841,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":54314,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":18,"outputTokens":6841,"cacheReadInputTokens":861833,"cacheCreationInputTokens":54314,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.9414939999999999,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000},"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":257,"outputTokens":19937,"cacheReadInputTokens":2462913,"cacheCreationInputTokens":116610,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.4919958,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"amendments":[{"body":"In `unique_terminal_replay_match` (fs.rs ~line 2832), the contract violation when `requested_run_id.is_some() && requested_started_at.is_none()` is handled by logging a `tracing::warn` and returning `None`. The caller then maps `None` to a generic 'no matching task run' error, losing the diagnostic information about the contract violation. Issue 2 specifies 'Replace any debug_assert! guards on this with runtime checks that return errors in both debug and release builds.' The current approach technically prevents the wrong behavior but the error message seen by callers/operators is misleading — it says 'no matching task run' when the real problem is a violated invariant. Change the function signature to return `Result<Option<usize>, AppError>` so the contract violation can propagate as a distinct error, or at minimum change the tracing level from `warn` to `error` since this represents a programming bug in a caller, not a recoverable warning.","rationale":"The spec explicitly requires runtime checks that 'return errors,' not silent None returns with warnings. While the current code is safe (callers always pass valid combinations today), if a future caller violates the contract, the resulting error message will be a red herring pointing at data corruption rather than the actual programming bug. This matters for debuggability in production."},{"body":"The `safe_plan_hash_backfill` function (fs.rs line 2608-2616) skips backfill when `snapshot_plan_hash_at_creation` is `None`, which means legacy open entries created before plan persistence was added will never get their `plan_hash` filled during completion, even though the current snapshot has the answer. The test `running_entry_created_before_plan_is_not_backfilled_on_revisit` explicitly asserts this behavior. However, Issue 3 acceptance criteria states 'Lineage entries auto-populate plan_hash from the milestone snapshot when callers omit it' — this is not true for existing legacy open entries with no provenance. Add a comment in the test and near the `safe_plan_hash_backfill` None branch explicitly documenting this as a deliberate deviation from the original issue spec, referencing the ambiguity rationale, so future reviewers don't re-open this as a regression.","rationale":"The current behavior is defensible (None provenance is ambiguous), but it's a conscious narrowing of Issue 3's scope. Without explicit documentation linking the decision back to the issue, a future developer reading Issue 3's acceptance criteria will see 'auto-populate plan_hash from the milestone snapshot when callers omit it' and file a bug against this code path. A comment costs nothing and prevents churn."}],"summary":"Reviewed the full diff (fs.rs + service.rs + model.rs) covering all three issues: (1) journal detail struct unification, (2) runless-to-named completion path, (3) plan_hash auto-population from snapshot. All 127 milestone_record tests pass. The one unrelated test failure (worktree_adapter checkpoint) is a pre-existing test isolation issue. Issue 1 (duplicate structs) is fully resolved — single definitions in model.rs, imported by fs.rs. Issue 2 (runless-to-named completion) is correctly implemented with started_at disambiguation, proper error paths, and no remaining debug_assert! calls. Issue 3 (plan_hash auto-population) works correctly for new rows and existing rows with provenance. Terminal replay correctly avoids auto-population. The service layer correctly passes plan_hash through unchanged, with auto-population happening at the adapter level. Two minor amendments proposed: (a) the contract violation in unique_terminal_replay_match uses warn+None instead of returning a typed error as the spec requires, and (b) the deliberate deviation from Issue 3 for legacy entries with no provenance should be explicitly documented."},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"c2393e30-30e3-4cc7-b822-f692a04ed2f2"}
